bout 1293–1343":"omkring 1293–1343","1291–1360":"1291–1360","1315–1343":"1315–1343","1320–1400":"1320–1400","1322–Male":"1322–Afdød","1324–Male":"1324–Afdød","1326–Male":"1326–Afdød","1330–Male":"1330–Afdød","1338–Male":"1338–Afdød","1293–1343":"1293–1343","about 1293":"omkring 1293","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1293":"1293","1291":"1291","1338":"1338","1315":"1315","1326":"1326","1324":"1324","1400":"1400","1322":"1322","1343":"1343","1320":"1320","Galway, County Galway, Ireland":"Galway, County Galway, Irland","Ireland":"Irland"},"nl":{"about 1293–1343":"circa 1293–1343","1291–1360":"1291–1360","1315–1343":"1315–1343","1320–1400":"1320–1400","1322–Male":"1322–Overleden","1324–Male":"1324–Overleden","1326–Male":"1326–Overleden","1330–Male":"1330–Overleden","1338–Male":"1338–Overleden","1293–1343":"1293–1343","about 1293":"circa 1293","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1293":"1293","1291":"1291","1338":"1338","1315":"1315","1326":"1326","1324":"1324","1400":"1400","1322":"1322","1343":"1343","1320":"1320","Galway, County Galway, Ireland":"Galway, County Galway, Ierland","Ireland":"Ierland"},"en":{"about 1293–1343":"about 1293–1343","1291–1360":"1291–1360","1315–1343":"1315–1343","1320–1400":"1320–1400","1322–Male":"1322–Deceased","1324–Male":"1324–Deceased","1326–Male":"1326–Deceased","1330–Male":"1330–Deceased","1338–Male":"1338–Deceased","1293–1343":"1293–1343","about 1293":"about 1293","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1293":"1293","1291":"1291","1338":"1338","1315":"1315","1326":"1326","1324":"1324","1400":"1400","1322":"1322","1343":"1343","1320":"1320","Galway, County Galway, Ireland":"Galway, County Galway, Ireland","Ireland":"Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Burgh","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from one or other of the ten English places named Burgh in northern England and East Anglia, or the six named Brough in Derbyshire, Nottinghamshire, Westmorland, and Yorkshire. All these are from Old English <i>burg</i>, <i>burh</i>, Middle English <i>burgh</i> ‘massive earthwork, fortification; manor, borough’. Compare   Bury  . The placename <i>Burgh</i> is pronounced as <i>borough</i>. The surname   Brough   arose equally from places now called Burgh and Brough, and is the more common form of the surname in modern Britain, where it is pronounced <i>bruff</i> or <i>broof</i> (/brʊf/). The Scottish surname was probably brought in from Yorkshire. For the surname in Ireland see   Burke  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Burke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Kieran, Siobhan, Aileen, Brennan, Brigid, Donovan, Liam, Murphy, Ulick, Aidan, Dermot.","English and Irish (of Anglo-Norman origin): habitational name from Burgh (Castle) in Suffolk, England. <i>Burk</i> represents an Anglo-Norman pronunciation of Old English <i>burg</i>, Middle English <i>burgh</i> ‘fortification’ (see   Burgh  ).","German: variant of   Burk  ."]},{"name":"Bury","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Bury in Lancashire (now part of Greater Manchester), or from some other similarly named place. The placename comes from the dative case, <i>byrig</i>, of Old English <i>burh</i> ‘fortified place’.","Walloon and French: habitational name from any of several places so named, in Wallonia (Belgium) and Oise (France). The placename is from <i>Buriacum</i>, the name of a Gallo-Roman estate, composed of the personal name <i>Burius</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>. This surname is also found in the Flemish part of Belgium.","South German: variant of   Buri  ."]},{"name":"Brough","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from any of various English places called Brough or Burgh. See   Burgh  .","Scottish: habitational name from Brough in Harray (Orkney).","Americanized form of German   Brauch   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Burrow","meanings":["English:","topographic name for someone who lived by a castle or manor house, or in a town, especially a chartered town or borough (Middle English <i>burgh</i>, Old English <i>burg</i> ‘fortified place, borough, manor’), or a habitational name for someone who came from a place so named because it was a fortified town or near an ancient fort, such as Burrow (Leicestershire, Lancashire), Burrough Green (Cambridgeshire), Brough (numerous counties), and Peterborough (Northamptonshire); see also   Burgh  .","topographic name for someone who lived on a hill or near a mound (Middle English <i>bergh</i>, Old English <i>beorg</i>), or a habitational name for someone who came from a place so named, such as Burrow (Devon, Somerset). Middle English <i>bergh</i> became throughly confused with <i>burgh</i> in 1 above. Compare   Burrough  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ismania de Burgh was born about 1293, in Ireland. She had at least 7 sons with Richard an Fhorbhair de Burgh. She died in 1343, in her hometown, at the age of 51."},"et":{"about 1293–1343":"umbes 1293–1343","1291–1360":"1291–1360","1315–1343":"1315–1343","1320–1400":"1320–1400","1322–Male":"1322–Surnud","1324–Male":"1324–Surnud","1326–Male":"1326–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1338–Male":"1338–Surnud","1293–1343":"1293–1343","about 1293":"umbes 1293","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1293":"1293","1291":"1291","1338":"1338","1315":"1315","1326":"1326","1324":"1324","1400":"1400","1322":"1322","1343":"1343","1320":"1320","Galway, County Galway, Ireland":"Galway, County Galway, Iirimaa","Ireland":"Iirimaa"},"fi":{"about 1293–1343":"noin 1293–1343","1291–1360":"1291–1360","1315–1343":"1315–1343","1320–1400":"1320–1400","1322–Male":"1322–Kuollut","1324–Male":"1324–Kuollut","1326–Male":"1326–Kuollut","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1338–Male":"1338–Kuollut","1293–1343":"1293–1343","about 1293":"noin 1293","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1293":"1293","1291":"1291","1338":"1338","1315":"1315","1326":"1326","1324":"1324","1400":"1400","1322":"1322","1343":"1343","1320":"1320","Galway, County Galway, Ireland":"Galway, County Galway, Irlanti","Ireland":"Irlanti"},"fr":{"about 1293–1343":"environ 1293–1343","1291–1360":"1291–1360","1315–1343":"1315–1343","1320–1400":"1320–1400","1322–Male":"1322–Décédé","1324–Male":"1324–Décédé","1326–Male":"1326–Décédé","1330–Male":"1330–Décédé","1338–Male":"1338–Décédé","1293–1343":"1293–1343","about 1293":"environ 1293","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1293":"1293","1291":"1291"